Mobile IPv6 example
===================

A basic Mobile IPv6 (RFC 3775) scenario: a mobile node (MN) moves between its
home network and a single foreign access network, registering a care-of address
(CoA) with its home agent and exchanging traffic with one or more correspondent
nodes (CN).

The mobile node uses TurtleMobility to dwell in each network for a while and then
dash to the other, looping forever, so the "at home / handing over / in the
foreign network" phases are easy to follow in Qtenv. Its current status -- the
associated access point and whether it is at home, away (tunneled via the home
agent), or route-optimized -- is shown above its icon.

Topology:

    CN --- switch --- R_2 --- Home_Agent --- AP_Home   (home network)
                       |
                       +----- R_1 ---------- AP_1       (foreign network)

R_2 is a backbone router interconnecting the home agent, the foreign access
router and the correspondent nodes. Addresses and routes are assigned by the
Ipv6NetworkConfigurator, configured with assignAddressesToHosts = false so that
hosts -- in particular the mobile node -- autoconfigure their home and care-of
addresses (SLAAC).

Configurations:

  Handover -- one correspondent node pings the mobile node's stable home address
    throughout. The replies reach it directly while it is home, then via the
    home-agent tunnel once it has registered a care-of address, and finally
    route-optimized directly to the care-of address.

  RouteOptimizationTwoCNs -- two correspondent nodes ping the mobile node while
    it is in the foreign network; each flow independently runs the return-
    routability procedure and route-optimizes with the mobile node.

Run:

    inet -u Cmdenv -c Handover

or open omnetpp.ini in the IDE / Qtenv and pick a configuration.

For a scenario with two foreign networks and two successive handovers, see the
mipv6roaming example.
